 12. Policies Toward Migrant Workers -- tChapter 13. Planning for Aging Involves Planning for Life -- tPART IV. Housing and Community -- tChapter 14. Public Housing in the United States: Neighborhood Renewal and the Poor -- tChapter 15. Neighborhood Social Mix: Theory, Evidence, and Implications for Policy and Planning -- tChapter 16. Suspicion, Surveillance, and Safety: A New Imperative for Public Space? -- tChapter 17. Beyond the Ladder: New Ideas About Resident Roles in Contemporary Community Development in the United States -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors of Policy, Planning, and People argue for the promotion of social equity and quality of life by designing and evaluating urban policies and plans. Edited by Naomi Carmon and Susan S. Fainstein, the volume features original essays by leading authorities in the field of urban planning and policy, mainly from the United States, but also from Canada, Hungary, Italy, and Israel. The contributors discuss goal setting and ethics in planning, illuminate paradigm shifts, make policy recommendations, and arrive at best practices for future planning.Policy, Planning, and People includes theoretical as well as practice-based essays on a wide range of planning issues: housing and neighborhood, transportation, surveillance and safety, the network society, regional development and community development. Several essays are devoted to disadvantaged and excluded groups such as senior citizens, the poor, and migrant workers. The unifying themes of this volume are the values of equity, diversity, and democratic participation. The contributors discuss and draw conclusions related to the planning process and its outcomes. They demonstrate the need to look beyond efficiency to determine who benefits from urban policies and plans.Contributors: Alberta Andreotti, Tridib Banerjee, Rachel G. Bratt, Naomi Carmon, Karen Chapple, Norman Fainstein, Susan Fainstein, Eran Feitelson, Amnon Frenkel, George Galster, Penny Gurstein, Deborah Howe, Norman Krumholz, Jonathan Levine, Anastasia Loukaitou-Sideris, Enzo Mingione, Kenneth Reardon, Izhak Schnell, Daniel Shefer, Michael Teitz, Iván Tosics, Lawrence Vale, Martin Wachs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCity planningzUnited States. 0aCity planning. 0aUrban policyzUnited States. 0aUrban policy. 4aUrban Studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aGeneral.  aPublic Policy.  aSocial Science.  aUrban Studies.1 aAndreotti, Alberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Tridib, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBratt, Rachel G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarmon, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarmon, Naomi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChapple, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFainstein, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFainstein, Susan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFainstein, Susan S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeitelson, Eran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrenkel, Amnon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalster, George C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurstein, Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrumholz, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l